title: Ephestia elutella
text:
Ephestia elutella, the cacao moth, tobacco moth or warehouse moth, is a small <a href="moth">moth</a> of the <a href="family%20%28biology%29">family</a> <a href="Pyralidae">Pyralidae</a>. It is probably native to Europe, but has been transported widely, even to <a href="Australia">Australia</a>. A <a href="subspecies">subspecies</a> is "E. e. pterogrisella".
The <a href="wingspan">wingspan</a> is 14–20 mm. This moth flies throughout the warmer months, e.g. from the end of April to October in <a href="Belgium">Belgium</a> and the <a href="Netherlands">Netherlands</a>.
The caterpillars are often considered a <a href="pest%20%28organism%29">pest</a>, as they feed on dry plant produce, such as <a href="cocoa%20bean">cocoa bean</a>s and <a href="tobacco">tobacco</a>, as well as <a href="cereal">cereal</a>s and <a href="dried%20fruit">dried fruit</a> and <a href="Nut%20%28fruit%29">nut</a>s. Less usual foods include dried-out meat and animal carcasses, specimens in <a href="insect">insect</a> collections, and dry <a href="wood">wood</a>.
